<Review ID>9043196
<Product Name>Apple 160 GB iPod classic (Black)
<Title>iPod Classic Skips
<Date>Sun Nov 25 00:00:00 CST 2007
<Content>All iPod Classics Skip  I have two iPods: * The iPod Classic Model A1238 - MB150LL, Firmware V1.0.2 PC, 6th generation and  * The older iPod 80G Model A1136 - MA450LL, Firmware V1.2.1, , 5th generation (the one with the glossy front face).    The new iPod Classic skips when playing WAV and other lossless file formats loaded via iTunes...but its predecessor does not.    I synced about 20G of the exact same lossless and MP3 music on both iPods (5G & 6G).    The older 80G iPod does not skip.   The iPod Classic 160G skips on all of the songs...  It skips on every song in exactly the same place every time I play the song.  By skipping, I mean, the song plays and then suddenly stops and the iPod goes on to the next song.    In iTunes, I can select the song in the iPod Classic library and it plays through the whole song on the PC.    I finally took the iPod classic back to Apple and they gave me a new one.  The replacement iPod Classic does exactly the same thing.  The songs skip in exactly the same place they did on the one I took back.    I've read on a bunch of web sites where a lot of other people have been having the same problem.  Technically it could be a parity problem, a certain bit configuration or something to do with the gapless feature of the iPod.    Apple suggested that I can fix the problem by take the original CD and rip it using iTunes and then syncing the iPod.  But if the CD has a tiny bad spot in it, the song will still skip.   Apple's stated solution for the skipping problem is to run (sync) the song through the MP3 compression using iTunes.    But, the reason for the 160G was to be able to load and play lossless files.    This has been a challenge since I bought the iPod Classic.  There are a bunch of us waiting for these problems with the iPod Classic to be fixed.    If you are considering purchasing an iPod for this purpose, save your money.   Apple has in essence said they have no intention of fixing this problem.     
<Overall>1

<Review ID>9535347
<Product Name>Apple 160 GB iPod classic (Black)
<Title>Objective review from a non apple fan
<Date>Sun Nov 25 00:00:00 CST 2007
<Content>First of all, I have to say that I'm not an apple fan. In fact, while most of my programmer and designer friends and professors are picking up their fav. apple gadget, I was still faithful to my zen player and blackberry curve(no iphone for me). Although I've been using many apple products for years(design/programming labs, using/fixing up my friends mbp, etc), this is the first apple product that I actually OWN.   I was surprised that I actually love this ipod. Size is my first priority. I have a huge collection of podcast, video, and music and have to store it in a movable storage and at the same time use in on the go. My 12" ultraportable can't keep up running around with me and storing in the ever growing collection and I have to get another solution. I have zen player for the past 2 years and it doesn't have enough space. After debating between this and ipod touch with its wifi capability, I decided this is the best deal.   There is nothing fancy in the box and no sleeves like the prev. generation. But I'm getting a case anyway. After few days of use there are certain things I noticed:  1. the back metal enclosure is very easily scratched. No matter how you tried to protect it , like putting it down on a soft fabric while waiting for your case to arrive, it will get fine scratches. you can't tell it at first, but look long enough under bright lights. between your prints (yes you will have your prints all over the metallic back, it doesn't look good), you will see fine lines.  2. ITunes is not the best software out there. The interface is very unintuitive. For example, it won't automatically recognize the song I have so I have to manually move them to itunes. Podcast download is horrible. When you click "get tracks" that means you won't be subscribed, but when you click "subscribed" you won't get all of the tracks. so it's double work. you have to click subscribe on the itunes store, then go back to your podcast and click get all tracks. once you are downloading your tracks, you can't just pause it, close itunes, and expect you can resume your downloads later (and mind you about the size of a video downloads). Podcasts downloads (but not subscription)will go under music not podcast if you only download the tracks without subscribing (which is a big problem in you download your university courses, the ITunesU). you have to subscribe for it to show in the podcast section. This cause confusion when you sync it with the ipod. you have to go through music playlist,not podcast to listen to your PODCAST.  3. must buy wall charger separately. I guess everyone can deal with this since the battery is pretty decent.  4. awful earphone. get a cheap earphone to replace apple earphone. I got a cheap sony sport earphone and it sounds much better. soon I'll get shure's noise canceling earphone.   5. just good enough music quality. solution? look at number 4.   6. Intuitive player interface. I must say this is one of the best player interface I've seen yet.   7. totally superficial side: no matching connector and apple earphone. I was expecting to get black apple earphone and black connector (now I realize it's an empty hope).   8. thin body for the storage size.  bottom line:  I would buy this again anytime. this is a good player for the price. it isn't that expensive either.   
<Overall>4

